WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.680
All right. Hello. I'm Kelly. I'm a professor at Cal Poly. It's about three and a half hours

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:16.760
south of here. And I'm going to tell you about some stuff. We are building five minutes.

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:23.840
So welcome to my infomercial. Here we go. So here is the thesis by which my collaborator

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:29.160
Hunter and I started this project. Things are hard. And things are extra hard for teachers

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:36.759
have no time for things and no resources sometimes for things like personal development and RStudio

00:00:36.759 --> 00:00:41.500
conferences. So we were like, how can we use R to make it easier for the other people in

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:47.320
our field? So we have two packages that are in infancy. And these two packages I'm going

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.240
to give you the shortest possible sneak preview. And then I'll tell you more about the one

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:56.119
that's not in infancy. So here's a thing that's hard if you are a basic R user. And I mean

00:00:56.119 --> 00:01:02.040
basic probably beyond anyone at this conference. Many of our collaborators or our colleagues,

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.199
they use R, they know it, by which I mean they can read in data and run a linear model.

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:11.160
Not much else. And they're very excited about Shiny, but the whole idea of Shiny is very

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:16.919
intimidating. So we're working on a package that the idea is, can we boil Shiny down to

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:22.000
something accessible by people at this very basic level? So the basic idea is to have

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.199
some kind of pipeline maybe that creates the app for you that writes the skeleton

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:29.599
code. Again, we have some of this running, but it's not public yet. And we're very open

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:33.239
to other ideas as well, thinking about ways to make it easier.

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:38.720
The second thing that's hard is updating course materials. Every single year you have to change

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:43.059
all the little details in your syllabus, even if the structure of it didn't change much.

00:01:43.059 --> 00:01:48.279
So package number two is called Templar for templates. And the idea is templating is really

00:01:48.279 --> 00:01:53.400
cool in RStudio and R Markdown. So one thing is there's package templates, so you could

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:58.120
auto-generate all the subfolders of your course file, and it would fill in the course name

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:03.040
in the right places. And then it would populate those folders then with R Markdown template

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:08.160
files that use YAML to kind of automate fillers. So this is a syllabus example. Made it as

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:12.199
big as I could and get everything in there, but the idea is the information that changes

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:16.559
quarter to quarter, year to year, you would just change in the YAML. Everything else you

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:20.880
could leave alone, and maybe it's even going to write tables and stuff automatically for

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:21.880
you.

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:26.000
All right. So that's your sneak preview. But what I am here to mostly tell you about is

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:33.360
Flare. Flare is a package that I'm very excited about. So this is something that maybe applies

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:37.279
to everyone in this room. Formatting source code for presentations. I've seen a lot of

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:41.600
presentations today. People are showing their source code. Sometimes what you want to do

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:47.080
is things like highlight the important parts of your source code, right? But this is very

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:52.600
frustrating sometimes. There's several problems with it. One is just the annoyance of what

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:56.600
most people do. What I used to do is copy paste the R code into like PowerPoint and

00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:01.199
manually highlight things or what have you. Perhaps more importantly to this community,

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:04.800
it's not reproducible. I don't know if you have done this. I have done this in class

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.639
where I decide to tweak something and I forget to tweak it in the PowerPoint or whatever,

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:14.119
and then my students are seeing code that doesn't match the graph. That's not great.

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:18.399
So this is how I feel.

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:21.960
And so we like to introduce Flare because you are adding kind of meaningless decoration.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:27.240
It does not change how the code runs and it does not change the internal, I don't know,

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:29.240
value of the code.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:32.919
And so how it works, very briefly, you have your code chunk. Nothing in this code chunk

00:03:32.919 --> 00:03:37.259
is new except that it's very important that you give it a name and important probably

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:41.059
that you turn off include unless you want it to be duplicated.

00:03:41.059 --> 00:03:44.500
And so we all love Iris. I only have five minutes. I can't tell you about new data sets.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:49.179
So suppose this is my code chunk. That's what it looks like. Step two is you call this decorate

00:03:49.179 --> 00:03:54.580
function that kind of preps that code chunk to be flared. And then all you have to do

00:03:54.580 --> 00:03:57.500
is add the flare that you want to this code chunk.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:01.660
So there's a whole suite of Flare functions. The basic one is just like directly Flare

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:05.979
a string. And then the other ones, we've got some shortcuts for like highlighting functions

00:04:05.979 --> 00:04:09.899
and stuff. So you might end up with something like this if you're trying to teach piping.

00:04:09.899 --> 00:04:13.820
Here's the functions that you're piping to. There's my pipes. Then we learn exciting new

00:04:13.820 --> 00:04:16.500
things about flowers.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:19.779
So that's it. That's all it takes. There's a lot more that I would love to tell you about

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:24.619
it, but that's the main deal. So I just, because there's no questions, I want to answer some

00:04:24.619 --> 00:04:27.459
things that you might want to know.

00:04:27.459 --> 00:04:32.820
Does it work in all the like R Markdown spin-offs? Mostly yes. These are in share engine. Obviously

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:38.980
I used Flare to flare my flare. But there's kind of a little complication where we sort

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:43.380
of have to hard code the way code gets formatted. That's not the same for every doc type. So

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:47.019
all you got to do is tell me what doc type you want, and I can easily add that in. But

00:04:47.019 --> 00:04:51.220
I have to know about that doc type to make it work.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:54.380
What happens when you, so this is for knitting, right? We want the knitted code to look good.

00:04:54.380 --> 00:04:58.700
What happens when you just run it actively? First of all, any code that you have, if you've

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:04.380
chosen to leave Evaluate on, it does run, so you can like reference objects. And it

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:09.059
previews how it's going to flare in your viewer pane, so you can check that without knitting.

00:05:09.059 --> 00:05:12.540
LaTeX is the next order of business. Crayon was going to be on two months ago, and then

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:17.619
I woke up at 3 a.m. with a whole plan of how to rebuild everything better. So imminently

00:05:17.619 --> 00:05:21.140
is the hope on Crayon. It's just about there.

00:05:21.140 --> 00:05:32.579
And that's all I have to say. Hex stickers. Sorry. Hex stickers are on the chair at the

00:05:32.579 --> 00:05:33.420
end if you want them.

